        Received message. Yes, you're correct. When we talk about centering an element like your `page-title`, it means that the element will be centered within its parent container, which could be the `body` of the page or another `div` depending on your HTML structure.

        If you use `text-align: center;` on your `page-title`, it will center the text within the `page-title` element itself. This is irrespective of whether it's stacked under the preceding `aside` elements or aligned horizontally for desktop.

        If you want to center the `page-title` element itself (not just the text inside it) within its parent container, you can use a combination of Flexbox properties on the parent container:

        ```css
        .parent-container {
        display: flex;
        justify-content: center; /* for horizontal centering */
        align-items: center; /* for vertical centering */
        }
        ```

        In this example, the `page-title` will be centered both horizontally and vertically within `.parent-container`, regardless of other elements around it.

        Remember, these CSS properties don't affect the position of other elements on the page. They only control the position of the targeted element within its parent container.
